---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const qrCells = Array.from({ length: 49 });
---
<BaseLayout
  title="SkanPay - QR Payment Gateway for In-Store Transactions"
  description="SkanPay helps merchants and payment partners support QR code payment experiences for in-store and mobile wallet transactions."
  activePath="/"
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">QR payment gateway</p>
      <h1>QR payment gateway for in-store and mobile wallet transactions</h1>
      <p class="hero-copy">
        SkanPay helps merchants and payment partners define the transaction path from QR presentation to customer authorization, merchant confirmation, and operational follow-up.
      </p>
      <div class="button-row">
        <a class="button primary" href="/contact/">Contact SkanPay</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href="/qr-payments/">Explore QR Payments</a>
      </div>
      <div class="trust-strip" aria-label="SkanPay focus areas">
        <div class="trust-item">
          <strong>01</strong>
          Merchant checkout
        </div>
        <div class="trust-item">
          <strong>02</strong>
          Wallet-ready QR flow
        </div>
        <div class="trust-item">
          <strong>03</strong>
          Partner integration support
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="mockup-shell technical" aria-label="QR payment terminal illustration">
      <div class="terminal-mockup">
        <div class="terminal-top">
          <strong>SkanPay Checkout</strong>
          <span>$24.80</span>
        </div>
        <div class="terminal-body">
          <div class="qr-grid" aria-hidden="true">
            {qrCells.map(() => <span></span>)}
          </div>
          <div class="payment-lines" aria-hidden="true">
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
            <div class="payment-status">Ready to scan</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="event-log" aria-label="Transaction event states">
        <div><span>01</span> qr_session.created</div>
        <div><span>02</span> customer.scan_received</div>
        <div><span>03</span> payment.authorization_pending</div>
        <div><span>04</span> merchant.confirmation_ready</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Transaction model</p>
        <h2>A readable flow for every party in the payment</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        The site now describes SkanPay as a gateway workflow: what is created, who acts next, and what the merchant needs to see before completing the sale.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="flow-table" aria-label="QR payment transaction model">
      <article>
        <span>Step</span>
        <strong>1. Present</strong>
        <p>Merchant creates or displays a checkout-specific QR code.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Step</span>
        <strong>2. Scan</strong>
        <p>Customer opens the payment request in a supported wallet or app.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Step</span>
        <strong>3. Authorize</strong>
        <p>Customer reviews the amount and approves or cancels the payment.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Step</span>
        <strong>4. Confirm</strong>
        <p>Merchant receives a clear status before closing the checkout.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section technical-band">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Implementation focus</p>
      <h2>Technical enough for partners. Simple enough for merchants.</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        SkanPay should make the QR payment workflow understandable before an integration discussion starts. Each page separates checkout behavior, partner responsibilities, and support expectations.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid three">
      <article class="card data-card">
        <span>Merchant</span>
        <h3>Checkout state</h3>
        <p>Clear payment status language for staff at the counter.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card data-card">
        <span>Customer</span>
        <h3>Scan and approve</h3>
        <p>A familiar mobile action connected to a visible request.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card data-card">
        <span>Partner</span>
        <h3>Integration boundary</h3>
        <p>Defined responsibilities for wallet, loyalty, or payment apps.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section split">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Gateway capabilities</p>
      <h2>What the site now makes easier to understand</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        The redesign avoids vague payment language and gives prospects a more concrete view of the system conversations SkanPay supports.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="spec-panel">
      <div class="spec-row">
        <span>QR session</span>
        <p>Create a payment request customers can open from the checkout counter.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="spec-row">
        <span>Authorization</span>
        <p>Describe the customer approval state without making unsupported processing claims.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="spec-row">
        <span>Confirmation</span>
        <p>Make merchant-facing success, failure, and pending states easy to reason about.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="spec-row">
        <span>Support path</span>
        <p>Route real merchant, wallet, and cooperation questions to SkanPay.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Site architecture</p>
        <h2>Pages organized around buyer questions</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        A visitor can move from business value to payment flow to partner fit without hunting through repeated text.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid three">
      <article class="card route-card">
        <span>/services</span>
        <h3>What SkanPay supports</h3>
        <p>QR payments, gateway planning, onboarding, and partner support.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card route-card">
        <span>/qr-payments</span>
        <h3>How the transaction works</h3>
        <p>Presentation, scan, authorization, confirmation, and follow-up.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card route-card">
        <span>/partners</span>
        <h3>Where integrations fit</h3>
        <p>Payment apps, wallets, and loyalty platforms entering in-store checkout.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Trust posture</p>
        <h2>Precise language, no inflated claims</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        Payment websites need clarity more than decoration. The copy is written to be useful without implying unverified processor, bank, or compliance capabilities.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid three">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>System language</h3>
        <p>Visitors see concrete transaction states instead of generic payment slogans.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Responsible scope</h3>
        <p>Security, reporting, and settlement language stays practical until specific integrations are confirmed.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Direct next step</h3>
        <p>Prospects can identify the inquiry type and send details to support@skanpay.us.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cta-band">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Next step</p>
      <h2>Bring QR payment conversations into focus.</h2>
      <p>Share the merchant, partner, or product details you want SkanPay to support and the team can follow up directly.</p>
    </div>
    <a class="button secondary" href="/contact/">Start a Conversation</a>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
